{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775842514224,"sessionID":"ses_2878abccdffeNin6MoIMg3IAy9","part":{"id":"prt_d7875ceaf001g2P6Xy85I5L8tD","messageID":"msg_d7875b72a001XxEOmb99gxkqwp","sessionID":"ses_2878abccdffeNin6MoIMg3IAy9","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_7380e773230b4d91be52e068","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Proposal: AR-005 — Sandbox 创建处理器\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement a Sandbox creation handler in `pkg/workloadmanager` that provides unified APIs for creating and managing sandbox environments based on AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter Kubernetes resources. The handler exposes high-level sandbox operations through the existing HTTP service framework.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nThe WorkloadManager module currently exposes low-level CRUD operations for AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources through the HTTP service framework (AR-004). However, users and external systems often need a higher-level abstraction that encapsulates the complexity of setting up a complete sandbox environment with proper configuration, dependencies, and lifecycle management.\n\n### Goal\n\nProvide a production-ready Sandbox creation handler that:\n- Offers unified, high-level APIs for sandbox environment creation\n- Supports multiple sandbox types (AgentRuntime-based, CodeInterpreter-based)\n- Handles resource dependency management and initialization sequencing\n- Provides sandbox lifecycle management (create, destroy, status, scaling)\n\n### Value\n- Simplifies sandbox provisioning for end users\n- Abstracts away Kubernetes resource complexity\n- Enables sandbox templates and presets for common use cases\n- Provides a clean separation between sandbox operations and low-level resource management\n\n---\n\n## Scope\n\n### In-Scope\n\n| Deliverable | Description |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| Sandbox CRD/Model | Domain model representing sandbox configuration and state |\n| Sandbox Manager | Core logic for sandbox creation, deletion, and lifecycle management |\n| Sandbox Handlers | HTTP handlers for sandbox REST APIs |\n| Template System | Support for sandbox templates with predefined configurations |\n| Dependency Management | Handle resource dependencies and initialization order |\n\n### API Endpoints\n\n#### Sandbox Management\n| Method | Path | Description |\n|--------|------|-------------|\n| POST | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxes` | Create a new sandbox |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxes` | List all sandboxes |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxes/{name}` | Get sandbox details |\n| DELETE | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxes/{name}` | Delete sandbox |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxes/{name}/status` | Get sandbox status |\n| PATCH | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxes/{name}/scale` | Scale sandbox resources |\n| POST | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxes/{name}/restart` | Restart sandbox |\n\n#### Sandbox Templates\n| Method | Path | Description |\n|--------|------|-------------|\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxtemplates` | List sandbox templates |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxtemplates/{name}` | Get template details |\n| POST | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/sandboxtemplates` | Create a template |\n\n### Code Structure\n\n```\npkg/workloadmanager/\n├── server.go                    # HTTP server (existing)\n├── service.go                   # WorkloadManager interface (existing)\n├── types.go                     # API types (existing)\n├── client.go                    # Kubernetes client (existing)\n├── sandbox/\n│   ├── manager.go               # Sandbox manager implementation\n│   ├── model.go                 # Sandbox domain model\n│   ├── handler.go               # HTTP handlers for sandbox APIs\n│   ├── template.go              # Template system\n│   └── template_handler.go      # Template HTTP handlers\n└── config/\n    └── config.go                # Configuration types\n```\n\n### Out-of-Scope\n- Container runtime implementation (handled by AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter)\n- Network policy management (future enhancement)\n- Persistent storage provisioning (future enhancement)\n- Multi-cluster sandbox management (future enhancement)\n- Sandbox monitoring and alerting (separate observability module)\n\n---\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n|------------|--------|---------|\n| github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go | local | Kubernetes typed client for AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter |\n| github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/workloadmanager | local | Existing WorkloadManager service |\n| k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/runtime | ^1.34 | Object serialization |\n| k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1 | ^1.34 | metav1 types |\n\n### Upstream Dependencies\n\n- **AR-004 WorkloadManager HTTP Service Framework** — Provides the HTTP server and client integration\n- **AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter CRDs** — Underlying Kubernetes resources managed by sandboxes\n\n### Downstream Consumers\n\n1. **User-facing CLIs** — Simplified commands for sandbox management\n2. **IDE integrations** — Create sandboxes for development environments\n3. **CI/CD pipelines** - Ephemeral sandboxes for testing\n4. **Multi-tenant platforms** - Isolated execution environments\n\n### Risks\n\n| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|------------|\n| Resource orphaning | High | Finalizers and cleanup handlers |\n| Template injection | Medium | Input validation and schema validation |\n| Concurrent operations | Medium | Optimistic locking with resourceVersion |\n| Cascading deletions | Medium | Explicit dependency tracking |\n\n---\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Option 1: Direct AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter Usage (Selected)\n\n**Approach**: Extend the existing WorkloadManager with sandbox-specific abstractions that wrap AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Reuses existing infrastructure from AR-004\n- Clear separation between low-level CRUD and high-level sandbox operations\n- Gradual implementation following the existing patterns\n- Type-safe with strong Kubernetes integration\n\n**Cons**:\n- Requires additional abstraction layer\n- May have slight overhead compared to direct access\n\n**Decision**: Selected — provides the best balance of simplicity and functionality.\n\n---\n\n### Option 2: Separate Sandbox Operator\n\n**Approach**: Implement a full Kubernetes operator for Sandbox resources with custom resource definition.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Native Kubernetes reconciliation patterns\n- Automatic reconciliation on resource changes\n- Standard operator lifecycle management\n\n**Cons**:\n- Higher complexity and development time\n- Requires separate deployment and maintenance\n- Overkill for current requirements\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — can be considered as a future enhancement.\n\n---\n\n### Option 3: Generic Resource Proxy\n\n**Approach**: Implement a generic proxy that transforms arbitrary resource requests into Kubernetes operations.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Highly flexible\n- Supports any resource type\n\n**Cons**:\n- Loses type safety\n- Complex validation logic\n- Harder to maintain and debug\n\n**Decision**: Rejected —牺牲 type safety for marginal flexibility.\n\n---\n\n### Option 4: External Sandbox Service\n\n**Approach**: Implement sandbox management as a separate microservice.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Complete isolation from workload manager\n- Independent scaling and deployment\n- Technology flexibility\n\n**Cons**:\n- Additional infrastructure complexity\n- Network latency between services\n- Requires service discovery and load balancing\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — adds unnecessary operational complexity for current scale.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: Core Model\n- [ ] Define `Sandbox` and `SandboxTemplate` domain models\n- [ ] Implement sandbox state machine (Pending, Running, Failed, Terminating)\n- [ ] Create validation logic for sandbox configurations\n\n### Phase 2: Sandbox Manager\n- [ ] Implement `SandboxManager` interface\n- [ ] Create sandbox from AgentRuntime template\n- [ ] Create sandbox from CodeInterpreter template\n- [ ] Implement sandbox lifecycle operations (create, delete, restart, scale)\n- [ ] Add status aggregation from underlying resources\n\n### Phase 3: HTTP Handlers\n- [ ] Add sandbox REST endpoints to server.go\n- [ ] Implement request/response mapping\n- [ ] Add watch support for sandbox status changes\n- [ ] Implement template management endpoints\n\n### Phase 4: Template System\n- [ ] Implement template CRUD operations\n- [ ] Add template validation and defaults\n- [ ] Support template inheritance/composition\n\n### Phase 5: Testing\n- [ ] Unit tests for sandbox manager\n- [ ] Integration tests with fake clientset\n- [ ] End-to-end tests with test Kubernetes cluster\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Sandbox creation creates appropriate AgentRuntime or CodeInterpreter resource\n- [ ] Sandbox status reflects aggregated state of underlying resources\n- [ ] Sandbox deletion properly cleans up all dependent resources\n- [ ] Sandbox templates can be created, listed, and used\n- [ ] All sandbox operations are properly logged\n- [ ] Error cases return appropriate HTTP status codes\n- [ ] Unit tests pass with >80% coverage for sandbox logic\n- [ ] Concurrent sandbox operations are handled correctly\n- [ ] Graceful shutdown properly terminates sandbox operations","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/workloadmanager/server.go\">\nERROR [13:2] could not import github.com/gin-gonic/gin (no required module provides package \"github.com/gin-gonic/gin\")\nERROR [64:58] server.handleListAgentRuntimes undefined (type *Ser